{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"75bb3843-5e81-48a0-a50f-91f6d9385e76","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options include:\n\n| Option | Flag |\n|---|---|\n| None (default) | `--auth None` |\n| Individual accounts | `--auth Individual` |\n| Azure AD (Entra ID) | `--auth SingleOrg` |\n| Azure AD B2C | `--auth IndividualB2C` |\n| Multi-org Azure AD | `--auth MultiOrg` |\n| Windows auth | `--auth Windows` |\n\n**Example:**\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth Individual\n```\n\nAdd `--use-minimal-apis` for minimal API style, or `--use-controllers` for controller-based. Use `dotnet new webapi --help` to see all options for your SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"367c976b-9cab-4d8d-9425-a9e2f5fc0a3c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":275,"requestId":"33CC:156A76:1F02212:22C9AC5:69E81959"},"id":"a319da3e-2b2e-4d96-bfbe-36e0ec3dce38","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:42:08.734Z","parentId":"fc764a58-e946-456b-85bb-e0e633b74f07"}
